  <div class="container">
    <div class="grid-2">
      <div>
        <h2 class="section-title">The Skeuomorphic Era</h2>
        <p>
          Before Flat Design, skeuomorphism dominated digital interfaces. Apps mimicked real-world 
          objects with leather textures, wood grain, and glossy buttons. Apple's iOS was the 
          epitome of this approach with its photorealistic icons and textures.
        </p>
        <p>
          While initially helpful for users transitioning from physical to digital, skeuomorphism 
          became increasingly criticized as dated, cluttered, and unsuitable for the diverse 
          screens of the mobile era.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <div class="card" style="background-color: var(--color-primary); color: var(--color-white);">
          <h3 class="card-title" style="color: var(--color-white);">Key Context</h3>
          <ul class="card-content" style="list-style: none; color: var(--color-white);">
            <li style="margin-bottom: var(--space-xs);"><strong>2010:</strong> Microsoft introduces Metro design</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: var(--space-xs);"><strong>2013:</strong> Apple launches iOS 7 with flat design</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: var(--space-xs);"><strong>Influence:</strong> Swiss modernism, Bauhaus</li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: var(--space-xs);"><strong>Goal:</strong> Digital-first, responsive interfaces</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--color-neutral);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title mb-lg">Timeline</h2>
    <div class="timeline">
      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">2006-2010</div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3>Skeuomorphism Peak</h3>
          <p>
            Apple's iOS dominates with hyper-realistic design. Leather, wood, and felt textures 
            are common. The digital world tries to look like the physical world. Critics begin 
            questioning the approach as screens diversify.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">2010</div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3>Metro Design Language</h3>
          <p>
            Microsoft introduces Metro design for Windows Phone 7. Features live tiles, bold 
            typography, and completely flat UI. Inspired by airport signage and Swiss design. 
            First major platform to embrace flat aesthetics.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">2011-2012</div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3>Web Design Shift</h3>
          <p>
            Web designers begin adopting flat aesthetics. Responsive web design becomes crucial. 
            Flat elements scale better and load faster than skeuomorphic graphics. The "Flat UI" 
            color palette becomes popular.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">2012</div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3>Windows 8 Launch</h3>
          <p>
            Microsoft expands Metro to desktop with Windows 8. Full commitment to flat, tile-based 
            interface. Controversial at first but establishes flat design as viable for major 
            operating systems. Influences entire industry.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">2013</div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3>iOS 7 Revolution</h3>
          <p>
            Apple abandons skeuomorphism completely with iOS 7. Jony Ive leads redesign featuring 
            flat colors, translucency, and minimal UI. Most dramatic design shift in iOS history. 
            Legitimizes flat design mainstream.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">2014</div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3>Material Design</h3>
          <p>
            Google introduces Material Design, adding subtle depth back with shadows and layers. 
            Called "Flat 2.0" or "Almost Flat." Balances flat aesthetics with usability cues. 
            Influences design systems industry-wide.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="timeline-item">
        <div class="timeline-year">2015-Present</div>
        <div class="timeline-content">
          <h3>Flat Design Maturity</h3>
          <p>
            Flat design becomes standard for web and app interfaces. Evolution continues with 
            subtle shadows and depth returning for usability. "Flat 2.0" approaches balance 
            aesthetic purity with functional clarity.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section" style="background-color: var(--color-white);">
  <div class="container">
    <h2 class="section-title">Key Figures & Platforms</h2>
    <div class="grid-3">
      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--color-primary);">
        <h3 class="card-title">Microsoft Metro Team</h3>
        <p class="card-content">
          Led by Microsoft Design Studio, created Metro design language for Windows Phone. 
          First major platform to commit fully to flat aesthetics. Inspired by Swiss design 
          and airport wayfinding systems.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--color-success);">
        <h3 class="card-title">Jony Ive</h3>
        <p class="card-content">
          Apple's Chief Design Officer who led iOS 7 redesign. Removed all skeuomorphic 
          elements Steve Jobs championed. Created Apple's flat design language still used 
          today with refinements.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--color-warning);">
        <h3 class="card-title">Matias Duarte</h3>
        <p class="card-content">
          Google's VP of Design who created Material Design. Evolved flat design by adding 
          subtle depth cues through shadows and motion. Balanced aesthetics with usability.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--color-danger);">
        <h3 class="card-title">Designmodo</h3>
        <p class="card-content">
          Created the influential "Flat UI" toolkit and color palette that became synonymous 
          with flat design. Popularized flat aesthetics among web designers worldwide.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--color-info);">
        <h3 class="card-title">Sacha Greif</h3>
        <p class="card-content">
          Designer and developer who popularized flat design through influential blog posts 
          and the "Flat UI Colors" palette. Helped define visual language of early flat design.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="card" style="border-left: 4px solid var(--color-turquoise);">
        <h3 class="card-title">Web Design Community</h3>
        <p class="card-content">
          Thousands of designers on Dribbble, Behance, and design blogs who experimented 
          with and evolved flat design principles. Created diverse interpretations of the style.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

